Security Requirement: Block all legacy authentication attempts tenant‑wide, without exception — except for emergency break‑glass accounts.


What Conditional Access CAN do: Block legacy authentication client types, Apply tenant‑wide, Exclude specific users (break‑glass), Apply to all cloud apps

What it CANNOT do: It does not impact service principals, It does not block modern OAuth with MFA, It should not be scoped per‑app (legacy auth is global)

Step‑by‑Step Implementation
Create break‑glass accounts

Minimum: 1
Recommended: 2


Deploy policy in Report‑Only via Graph
Go to https://aka.ms/ge

Sign in with admin account
Set API version to v1.0
Click Modify permissions
Add and Consent to: Policy.ReadWrite.ConditionalAccess

1. HTTP Method: POST
2. Endpoint: https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/identity/conditionalAccess/policies
3. JSON

Create policy using JSON
Set state:
JSON "state": "enabledForReportingButNotEnforced"

Step 3 – Validate in Sign‑in Logs
Microsoft Entra ID
→ Sign‑in logs
→ Conditional Access tab
→ Report‑only

Confirm:
Legacy auth attempts → Blocked (Report‑only)
Modern auth → Allowed

Step 4 – Remediate legacy usage
Before enforcing, identify and fix:

Old mail clients
Network devices using SMTP AUTH
Scripts using basic auth


Step 5 – Enforce policy
Update:
JSON "state": "enabled" 

Legacy auth is now fully blocked tenant‑wide.


Explanation of Key JSON Fields
clientAppTypes
"exchangeActiveSync" → legacy EAS
"other" → all remaining legacy protocols (POP, IMAP, SMTP AUTH, older Office)

These two values together fully cover legacy authentication.
includeApplications: ["All"]
Required — legacy auth isn’t app‑specific
Never select individual apps

excludeUsers
Only break‑glass human user accounts
Never exclude groups
Never exclude “All admins”

state
enabledForReportingButNotEnforced → report‑only
Change to enabled after validation



